{#
   rag/fallback.j2
   Response when retrieval confidence is too low to give a
   reliable commercial crop disease diagnosis.

   UPDATED: Now references commercial crops specifically and
   gives Uganda-relevant advice for when to seek help.

   Variables:
   - confidence_score: float
   - threshold: float
   - personality: communication style
#}

The retrieval confidence for this commercial crop image was
{{ confidence_score | round(2) }}, which is below our minimum
threshold of {{ threshold }}.

{% if personality == "friendly" %}
I was not able to find a confident enough match in our commercial
crop disease database to give you a reliable diagnosis this time.

This does not mean your crop has a serious problem — it may simply
mean the photo needs to be clearer or taken from a different angle.

Here is what I recommend:

1. Retake the photo in good natural daylight
2. Get closer to the most affected leaf or area
3. Make sure the affected part fills the photo clearly
4. Try selecting the correct crop type from the list

If you are still worried about your crop, please:
- Contact your nearest agricultural extension officer
- Visit your local agro-vet for advice
- Call the Uganda National Agricultural Advisory Services (NAADS)
- Bring a fresh sample of the affected plant to an agrochemical shop

Your crop and your harvest matter — don't hesitate to get help! 🌾

{% elif personality == "formal" %}
Insufficient retrieval confidence to generate a reliable diagnosis
for this commercial crop sample.

Confidence score: {{ confidence_score | round(2) }}
Minimum required: {{ threshold }}

Recommended actions:
1. Resubmit with a higher resolution image of the affected area
2. Ensure affected leaf tissue is clearly in frame without shadow
3. Specify the exact commercial crop type for better search precision
4. Consult a certified agronomist or extension worker for field inspection

{% elif personality == "concise" %}
Low confidence: {{ confidence_score | round(2) }} / {{ threshold }}.

Retake photo in good lighting.
Or contact your local extension officer for field diagnosis.
{% endif %}
